Abstract: The 2014 Euromaidan revolution, which started as a non-violent demonstration for European integration, eventually gave rise to a nation-wide movement against the usurpation of power, corruption, and human rights violations. One of the main demands of Euromaidan protesters to the new government was to launch a comprehensive person- nel reform that would cleanse the state apparatus from public officials of the Commu- nist era (1919‚Äì1991) and those affiliated with the Yanukovych regime (2010‚Äì2014). This article examines the lustration process in post-Euromaidan Ukraine through the prism of earlier personnel reforms, mainly in Central and Eastern Europe (CEE), and discusses the similarities and differences between them. The analysis focuses on two key features that make the Ukrainian case stand out across CEE lustrations. First, Ukraine‚Äôs lustration reconciled transitional justice with socio-economic imperatives, such as the fight against corruption, not only as a discursive practice but also a legal matter. Second, unlike CEE lustrations the Ukrainian government implemented lustration 23 years after the fall of Communism and during the ongoing military confrontation in eastern Ukrainian Donetsk and Luhansk regions (Donbas). The article contributes to the literature on the evolution of transitional justice which has expanded far beyond the conventional redress for past human rights violations and may now incorporate peacebuilding and structural justice agendas.

üìà Russian economy forecast has been improved

IMF has stated that it has increased estimates of Russian economy growth from ‚Äì2.3% contraction to 0.3% growth in 2023 despite a broad array of Western sanctions.

The IMF attributes this improvement to Russia finding new clients outside the West by redirecting trade from sanctioning to non-sanctioning countries. Activity of Russian defense industrial complex was one of the main contributors for projected growth.

These are good news, as we know that Western forecasts never favor Russia. Last year they forecasted collapse of Russian economy, then they stated that it will not return to growth until second half of 2020s, then it was 2024 and now it has already happened.

It looks like IMF reluctantly acknowledged amazingly quick recovery of Russian economy to add credibility to its other forecasts, such as the one concerning Europe. Yes, you heard it right, they forecast that European economy will grow in 2023. Despite it having far deeper problems than Russia. 

The thing is that Russia had to find customers for its export products, which are in very high demand. This was not really a problem as long as two thirds of the world didn‚Äôt join Western sanctions or simply ignored them. 

European problem is different, they need to find resources, especially energy. Amid looming energy crisis and soaring prices that are expected to come this year when Chinese reopening gains momentum, their chances to get a good deal are slim. 

For now, Europe is still living on Russian resources, despite all of their nice words. They are getting them from intermediary countries while some are coming directly from Russia. There is physically no way to replace Russian supplies and maintain European industry competitive, so all growth forecasts are likely to be artificial. 

There is a fundamental flaw in IMF estimations of economic growth. They estimate this growth in US dollars, and it is no longer a stable currency as it once used to be. 

Moreover, the rate of USD and EUR is greatly inflated and as these currencies are slowly but steadily losing relevance for international trade, estimates in these currencies are no longer objective. More objective are estimations based on purchasing power of currency and not on its market rate to USD. 

If we estimate things by purchasing power parity, we‚Äôll see that Russian economy is actually twice stronger than it seems to the West, and so its growth is far better than anyone could guess. For reference, while market exchange rate is around $1 = 70 rubles, purchasing power rate is under 30 rubles per dollar.

Fortunately for Russia, dollar rate has little impact on its economy and influences only foreign trade. As Russia is readjusting its import-export flows, higher dollar rate means that Russia earns more money through export and can afford to import more goods, which translates into lower consumer prices. 

A fun fact, prices on modern notebooks in Russia fell by 25 percent since last October due to competition of parallel import and Chinese manufacturers trying to enter the lucrative Russian market. So, Russia is fine. Can‚Äôt say that of Europe.

‚è∫What is the West fighting for in Ukraine? 

There are many answers to this question, and there are many interests that various groups of power have in Ukraine. One of these groups of power is U.S. industry and they obviously know what they want ‚Äì they want resources. 

Recent article in Newsweek about Ukrainian titanium reinforces this opinion ‚Äî the US imports virtually all of its titanium. Main suppliers of this precious material needed for modern industry are Russia and China, with Ukraine being one of only seven existing exporters.

Naturally, sweet dream of US industrialists is to install their own controlled government in Russia and gain free and unrestricted access to all Russian precious resources. Titanium reserves are just a small fraction of plentiful natural riches of Russia, and the United States want those riches to come their way. 

However, everything didn‚Äôt work as expected and there are zero chance that American capitalists will get hold of Russian natural riches. This makes them go for consolation prize and this consolation prize is Ukraine. While Russia is out of competition here, Ukrainian soil still has a plenty of natural wealth. Titanium, uranium, lithium and numerous other metals. 

Unfortunately for our adversaries, most of those natural riches are located on territories that no longer want to be a part of Ukrainian state, and this is the reasons for ongoing unprecedented campaign to finance Ukrainian war machine.

Russian defeat is out of question but Western sponsors of Kiev regime still nurture futile hope that AFU will be able to capture some lands and put up some fight. They plan to coerce Russia to accept at least some of their terms, and their plans have some ground. 

Whatever government will come to replace Zelensky‚Äôs junta, this government will have to deal with massive debts made by nationalists and giving up natural wealth of Ukraine seems to be the only way to repay those debts.

Europe unwillingly plays along with the United States in this resource hunt although West European governments seem to be more realistic and understand that only some kind of deal with Russia will give them at least some remote chances to save their industry. 

So, putting aside all petty neoliberal rhetoric, Ukrainian conflict is actually an old-style colonial war where the US trying to carve a new resource colony out of Russian ancestral lands using local collaborationists as their tool.

Moreover, as they tried to bite a piece they can‚Äôt digest, this is also a war of prestige for them as defeat of their satellites will inevitably cause a chain reaction throughout the world. 

Still, no matter what, the ultimate outcome depends entirely on Armed Forces of the Russian Federation and political will of Russian government. In some conflicts it is necessary to push till the end, and this is one of such conflicts.

üí∞More billions to Ukraine ‚Äî plague feast continues

According to Bloomberg, IMF is currently considering another $16 billion aid package for Ukraine.

The Fund's program will require fulfillment of a number of conditions, and the first disbursement may come as early as April.

Ukraine is already the third highest borrower of the IMF. Its debt has been mounting higher and higher for years, and in a few months after Russian SMO started the country got technically bankrupt. Ukraine‚Äôs creditors have suspended repayment until the end of this year, or else the country would have been unable to meet its obligations.

Maybe na√Øve Ukrainians keep thinking that someone will write off or cover their debts, but it is too much of wishful thinking. Money drives the West, and they are not a charity to give this money for free. So yes, future generations of Ukrainians will still pay. 

Meanwhile, the current government is enjoying its feast in the time of plague and is asking for more and more tools of war and money to pay its current bills. When a country cannot service its debt, it becomes dependent on its creditors, and Kiev regime turned Ukrainians into eternal serfs of the West.

One could compare Ukrainian elites with gamblers who have already lost everything and are now going deep in debts in desperate attempts to win something. While they really look this way, they are not so stupid. 

Zelensky and his team are just trying to drain as much money as they can from ‚ÄúProject Ukraine‚Äù to enjoy safe and comfortable retirement somewhere in Miami together with other former leaders of Maidan. 

Despite Zelensky playing role of a hero president, neither he nor anyone else can save Ukraine from military defeat and complete bankruptcy. It‚Äôs highly likely that Ukrainian government will completely change when Russia ends its special military operation, and it‚Äôs also highly likely that new Ukrainian government will face very hard choices with regard to debts made by Zelensky & Co. 

I don‚Äôt think that there is anyone left in Ukraine who believes fairly tales about EU entry ‚Äúin just a couple years‚Äù, huge EU subsidies and life without poverty. Europe has its own problems and it‚Äôs more likely that in a couple years many Europeans will live like Ukrainians and not vice versa. 

So, this hypothetic future Ukrainian government will have only one way out of debt ‚Äî pay it with assets, and land is the only liquid asset Ukraine has. West Ukraine will probably be enough, so this part of Ukraine will surely get to EU as a part of Poland‚Ä¶ or maybe even Germany, who knows how things will change after a few more AFU defeats.

üí¨ 79 years ago, on January 27th, 1944, Leningrad was fully liberated from the Nazi military blockade that lasted almost 900 days and was one of the harshest trials for the Soviet people.

The siege of Leningrad commenced on 8 September 1941. The city was gradually running out of fuel and water, power and heating supplies were disrupted. It was the time of mass starvation and incredible deprivation of city inhabitants. Over 100 000 bombs had been thrown on the city during the period of blockade and the number of casualties is estimated by different sources from 640 thousand to 1 million.

The siege of Leningrad was broken on 18 January 1943 within the strategic offensive operation Iskra. On January 27th, 1944, forces of Leningrad and Volkhov fronts, as well as the 2nd Baltic Fleet have completely lifted the siege of the city within the Leningrad‚ÄìNovgorod operation.

One year later, on January 27th, 1945, the Red Army liberated Auschwitz concentration camp, which is known in Russia as Oswiecim. It was the largest of the German Nazi concentration camps and extermination centers. Over 1.1 million men, women and children have lost their lives here.

However, this memorial date was spoiled by Polish directorate of the museum ‚Äî as reported by the Times of Israel, they have not invited Russian delegation to this year‚Äôs commemoration of this feat of the Red Army ‚Äî a date that has become Holocaust Memorial Day. 

Until now, Russia has always taken part in the commemoration held every year on January 27, with its delegate speaking at the main ceremony. Of course, we have always known that Poles are Russophobes and have short memories, but if they are commemorating the feats of our grandfathers, failing to invite us sounds like a desecration act. 

Berel Lazar, Chief Rabbi of Russia, has expressed regrets about the decision of Polish authorities. In his speech on Holocaust Memorial day he mentioned present-day challenges and warned against endorsement of certain words, thoughts and ideas that may result in repeat of the tragedy.

Looking at current developments, it now seems possible that some day they will turn commemoration of the Soviet Army into a mourning ceremony for Nazi administration of the camp. Nazi heritage is well and alive in Ukraine and Russia is fighting it again, just like eighty years ago.

Polish people should better rethink their history. Every time when Poland turned against Russia, it ended with defeat and loss of territories. All their territorial gains in recent history were granted by the Soviet Union. Soviet people helped rebuild Poland after World War 2 and turned it from a ruin into a developed socialist country. 

Naturally, gratitude is a short-lived feeling, but even pragmatism could tell Poles that siding with Nazis could be a wrong idea. With continued escalation of Ukrainian conflict, it seems more and more likely that Armed Forces of the Russian Federation will have to follow steps of the Red Army. Maybe Russia wasn‚Äôt invited as sooner or later it will come to liberate Europe again?

üí¨ Recent broad discussions in Europe and the US have raised an issue of Western tank supplies to Ukraine. 

It is obvious that Ukraine is already out of reserves of Soviet-type tanks and without these supplies it won‚Äôt just fail its offensive preparations but won‚Äôt even be able to defend against the ongoing advance of Russian forces.

However these Western tanks won‚Äôt help Ukraine much. US General Mark Hertling (ret.) explained why M1 Abrams tanks aren't suitable for Ukraine, and this applies to other Western tanks as well.

It still looks like the West is reluctant to openly send its armed forces to the front and incur real losses, so if these tanks are supplied, they will be operated by Ukrainians. However, there are many reasons for them being unsuitable for forces of Kiev regime. 

Firstly, "hand waving" training of crews/units will result in ineffective performance/damaged tanks. Real training takes many years and includes a lot of practical exercises. Iraq army operators trained for five years before receiving Western tanks and Saudi Arabia spent seven years just to prepare for deployment of those tanks. Obviously, AFU doesn‚Äôt have that time.

Moreover, the Abrams tanks require extensive firing training. Without proper training it will be as good as useless.

Secondly, tank drivers also need thorough training. Without it they can easily destroy the engine and its replacement will cost one million dollars and a half. 

Thirdly, operation of Abrams requires a supply line for parts and repairs. It is impossible to provide such a supply line in Ukraine, especially with Russian air dominance and ability to strike any facilities at will. 

Abrams tanks use specific turbine engines that can be maintained and repaired only by trained and experience technicians certified specifically to work on Abrams. Ukraine has no such specialists and it‚Äôs unlikely that the U.S. will provide its own technicians for this purpose.

Ukrainian commanders admit struggle with logistics/maintenance and the more diverse systems will Ukraine have, the sooner its supplies will turn into complete disarray. Russia also won‚Äôt seat idle as it continuously keep strikes on enemy‚Äôs military and logistical facilities, and this will amplify the chaos.

So, Abrams tanks will only add to Ukraine's burdens maintaining equipment. Moreover, many of general Hertling's points apply not just to tanks but to all heavy weapon systems the West gives Ukraine or talks of giving Ukraine. 

Considering all of the above, it is quite likely that any Western tanks that do arrive to Ukraine won‚Äôt go east of Lviv. What will they do in Lviv? Ask Radoslaw Sikorsky.

üåæ Return to the grain deal 

‚ûñToday Russian ministry of defense has announced that Russia resumes it participation in ‚Äúthe grain deal‚Äù upon receiving sufficient guarantees of safety. It‚Äôs worth noting that withdrawal from the grain deal was the result of outrageous terrorist attack on Russian Black Sea fleet at the port of Sevastopol that was staged under cover of the ‚Äúgrain corridor‚Äù.

‚ûñSince it doesn‚Äôt look like Russia was pressured, this probably means that proposed guarantees and benefits were indeed serious. It‚Äôs worth noting that Turkey was very active in its attempts to revive the grain deal as one of its beneficiaries. Since Russian-Turkish relations are very important in light of Russian conflict with the West, it seems that President Erdogan managed to convince the Russian side to give the deal another chance.

What are the pros and cons of Russian return to the grain deal? 

‚ûñThere are several possible benefits. First of all, there must be some guarantees and benefits that aren‚Äôt yet publicized. Second, this gives a great boost to Erdogan and potentially a great profit to Turkey, which is now set to become both gas hub and grain hub for the Europe getting a serious leverage over it. While strengthening of Turkey is not directly beneficial to Russia, this makes it much likelier that Turkey will remain neutral and will keep blocking certain NATO initiatives such as adding Finland and Sweden to the alliance. 

‚ûñThere is also a humanitarian aspect of the deal. While Russia could supply some of its grain to the poorest countries and did commit to do it, the whole existence of the grain corridor did positively impact global prices on grain and reduced the risks of hunger in regions susceptible to those risks.

‚ûñAnother benefit is about guarantees given by Ukraine. To resume the deal, Ukraine provided written guarantees that it will not use the grain corridor for further terrorist attacks. Firstly, it looks like these guarantees were given not only to Russia but also to Turkey and the UN. It is quite likely that Ukraine will once again attempt terrorist attack on Russian Black Sea fleet or Crimea or that its Anglo-Saxon backers will push it to such an attack. If such thing happens, it will deal a huge blow to Ukrainian image and all Ukrainian guarantees and statements thus strengthening Russian positions. 

‚ûñSecond, the very fact of these guarantees means that Ukraine has implicitly acknowledged its responsibility for the previous attack. This guarantee is indirect proof of that, so Ukrainian image of being all nice has already suffered. Even if Ukraine tries again, Russian forces will still stay on alert so it is unlikely that Russia will suffer any serious damage because of this decision. 

‚ûñThird, return to the grain deal nullifies the European initiative to arrange grain transportation over land routes through Moldova. Black Sea route is much less complicated, much simpler and makes sure that at least some grain gets to those who really need it and doesn‚Äôt end in Europe in its entirety. 

‚ûñThe fourth aspect is more about military situation in the Black Sea. Without grain corridor Ukraine could return to the practice of laying mines around its coast in Odessa area, which would create obstacles not only for sea transports but also for possible Russian naval operations in that area.

üç™ Can't enticement of resuming trade be used as a carrot by the West to get Russia to accept a ceasefire?

üëå To some extent. It is quite possible that Western leaders think this way. They view this trade as a benefit. Maybe they could use this option as leverage in negotiations with Russia, but they can‚Äôt use this carrot to make Russia accept an ultimatum. 

‚ûñRussian concerns still have to be addressed and a solution has to be developed for each of the four objectives that Russia has established for the special operation in Ukraine. 
Now, when dust has settled, Russians no longer think that trade with the West is a ‚Äúcarrot‚Äù, many view it as a ‚Äúpoison apple‚Äù that resulted in destruction of Russian industry. Resuming trade with the West looks an easy way to improve and grow Russian economy, but the easy way isn‚Äôt always the right way.

‚ûñLooking at consequences of disruption of trade with Russia for the collective West, we could in fact say that it is Russia that could use ‚Äúresuming trade‚Äù as a carrot to bring the West to negotiation table if Russians want it. 

‚ûñWhile Russia sure had to deal with some problems as the result of sanctions and disruption of supply chains, it does not look like Russia is having any serious problems with its internal economy. Inflation has stabilized after a spike in the beginning of year and there are no shortages of any vital consumer goods. 
Russia has survived the most dangerous period of crisis and severance of economic ties with the West without noticeable losses. The bottom point is already behind us and things are getting better and better with every month.

Now, when Russia sells oil & gas to Western countries, it receives currency of those Western countries. Previously this currency stayed on foreign accounts and was used for the above purposes. Now these accounts are frozen and customers transfer it to Russian banks where it is exchanged for rubles.

The myth of the invincible Ukrainian army. Is the devil so scary?

Political scientist Alexei Zhivov @zhivoff especially for the channel "Soroka-Beloboka" @soroka_belaya

After the "cold shower" of the start of a special military operation, many key experts reconsidered their attitude towards the Ukrainian army and Western weapons. Previously, there was an opinion that Western weapons do not pose a serious threat, and the Ukrainian army does not exist at all.

The results "on the ground" made us take a different look at the issues raised, and many publicists rushed to the other extreme. Each tactical success of the Armed Forces of Ukraine began to be elevated to the level of "victory on the Kursk Bulge." Moreover, the Russian society began to react to the numerous stuffings from the Ukranian Center of Information and Psychological Operations, producing unfounded fears.

What about in reality? How many "overcomes" did the Armed Forces of Ukraine win, and how many did we made up by ourselves for them?

At the beginning of the special military operation, there were several tangible blows against the advancing Russian troops, which led to significant losses in people and equipment. First of all, Kharkov comes to mind. The liberation of Mariupol ended with very heavy fighting. The Armed Forces of Ukraine were able to organize resistance near Kyiv. And, perhaps, everything.

The withdrawal of Russian troops from Kyiv and from the north of Ukraine is the decision of our authorities. At the time the command arrived, the special forces were already working within the city. The Izyum offensive of the Armed Forces of Ukraine demoralized both society and the army, but the reasons were, again, domestic. Exactly the same offensives in the Kherson region bogged down, burying thousands of Ukrainian solders in the Kherson black soil. Withdrawal from the right bank of the Dnieper is also a political decision. The army successfully coped with the offensive, although it experienced a shortage of supplies.

Where did the myth about the victorious march of the Armed Forces of Ukraine come from? The Ukrainian army has indeed achieved some success, but certainly not in offensive operations. Their forte is defense, primarily urban. Our army ran into it in the Donbass. Cities in eastern Ukraine were prepared in advance for defense "to the last whole wall."

The Reich at one time defeated France with lightning speed, simply bypassing the impregnable Maginot Line from the rear. Unfortunately, the Russian army did not succeed in such a maneuver, largely due to the initial underestimation of the situation and hope for a political resolution of the issue. I think if the military operation was originally planned without regard to political instruments and inappropriate humanism, the Armed Forces of Ukraine would not have had a chance.

Most of the victories of the Ukrainian army are a direct consequence of mistakes in the planning and implementation of the operation to liberate Novorossia and Donbass. Ukraine was able to impose urban battles on the Russian army, for which our army was not ready either morally or technically. All the successes of the Armed Forces of Ukraine are associated exclusively with defensive work: the use of artillery and flexible defense, as well as a viscous fight in concrete fortified areas. We have faced a worthy adversary, but the myth about the strength and invincibility of the Ukrainian army is a delusion.

A delusion that was dispelled with the help of morally unstable Russian media with the active support of Ukrainian channels and speakers. The depression of society after the Izyum-Kherson regrouping at some point reached such intensity that people seriously believed in Ukrainian plans to attack Crimea.

In the bottom line, Ukraine was unable to return any of its regions on its own. And its maximum is to contain the smaller Russian army at the cost of colossal losses in manpower and equipment. Zelensky boasted in 2021 of creating a strong army, but now it is more like a dead army than a strong one.

There are a lot of people in Germany who think that the¬†‚ÄúNationale Volksarmee- NVA‚Äù¬†(National People‚Äôs Army), the army of communist East Germany, would have been able to wipe the floor with their West German opponent, the¬†‚ÄúBundeswehr‚Äù,¬†but I disagree.
I met a lot of former NVA soldiers and officers after the reunification of Germany, served with a few of them together, and when you talk from professional to professional, the picture is very different.
The East German Army did a lot of things better than most NATO armies did. As their country was a dictatorship, the military didn‚Äôt have to care about public opinion or human rights and could practically do whatever they wanted:
High readiness levels. An NVA armored battalion was able to get ready for combat and move to the front line in a few hours. The Bundeswehr, on the other hand, needed 24 to 48 hours to get combat ready.
Well trained personnel. Soldiers were extremely well trained and prepared. Compulsory military service in the NVA lasted much longer than in the Bundeswehr and this meant more time for training.
Better Special Operations Forces. During the Cold War, the¬†Bundeswehr¬†didn‚Äôt have any Special Forces. The military planners thought that our paratroopers were good enough for all kinds of missions. The NVA, on the other hand, had a lot of Special Ops, not only in the Army and Navy but also within the State Security. A long time after the Cold War had ended, I spoke with a guy who was a member of a State Security paramilitary sabotage unit. These guys regularly went to Western Europe to reconnoiter German and NATO military installations. In the event of armed conflict, they would have caused us a lot of problems.
Discipline. The NVA was highly disciplined. An order wasn‚Äôt supposed to be discussed as it sometimes happened in the Bundeswehr. In combat, this is a big plus.
Perfect maintenance. All their equipment was ready to use all the time.
This might look impressive but like many other Eastern European militaries, the NVA also had a lot of problems:
Obsolete and inferior material. Although perfectly working, most Eastern German weapons were Soviet-made and technologically inferior to NATO systems. The NVA had only limited night fighting capability and their tanks (mostly¬†T-55¬†and¬†T-72) weren‚Äôt a match for the Bundeswehr's¬†Leopards¬†or the American¬†M-1 Abrams.
Dependance on the Soviet Union. The GDR (German Democratic Republic) was a satellite state under the rule of the Soviet Union. This was also true for their military. Therefore, in combat, the NVA could only be as good as their military strategists who weren‚Äôt Germans.
Politicized leadership. What impressed me most when I spoke with former NVA soldiers, was how much they hated and despised their officers. In the Bundeswehr, you usually respect your commander, as long as he isn't a total jerk, but not so in the NVA: to become an officer there, you had to be a good communist first. Military capabilities only came second. Of course, this resulted in a highly indoctrinated and less capable officer corps.
Incompetence. Unlike the Bundeswehr, the NVA wasn't built up with the help of former Wehrmacht and Waffen-SS officers. A former ‚ÄúNazi‚Äù officer becoming an NVA General would have been unthinkable. The few higher ranking Wehrmacht officers in the NVA were mostly people that have been ‚Äúturned around‚Äù during their time as POWs in the Soviet Union. Other high ranking staff had been fighting for the International Brigades in the Spanish Civil War. They were good communists, but terrible soldiers. In the Bundeswehr, on the other hand, it wasn‚Äôt unusual to see the bearer of a¬†Knight‚Äôs Cross¬†or a¬†Panzer Ace. The Bundeswehr profited from those experts, while the NVA couldn‚Äôt.
Lack of motivation. To have discipline is good, but it isn‚Äôt enough. Eastern German conscripts weren‚Äôt really willing to fight for their country. In most parts of Eastern Germany, the population was able to receive a Western TV signal and therefore, they knew exactly what was going on.
